[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:clap-cli-rust/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] In computer programming, **standard streams** are preconnected input and output communication channels between a computer program and its environment when it begins execution.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] The three input/output (I/O) connections are called **standard input** (**stdin**), **standard output** (**stdout**) and **standard error** (**stderr**).
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Originally I/O happened via a physically connected system console (input via keyboard, output via monitor), but standard streams abstract this.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] When a command is executed via an interactive shell, the streams are typically connected to the text terminal on which the shell is running, but can be changed with redirection or a pipeline.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] More generally, a child process inherits the standard streams of its parent process.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Users generally know standard streams as input and output channels that handle data coming from an input device, or that write data from the application.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] The data may be text with any encoding, or binary data.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] When a program is run as a daemon, its standard error stream is redirected into a log file, typically for error analysis purposes.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Streams may be used to chain applications, meaning that the output stream of one program can be redirected to be the input stream to another application.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] In many operating systems this is expressed by listing the application names, separated by the vertical bar character, for this reason often called the pipeline character.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] A well-known example is the use of a pagination application, such as more, providing the user control over the display of the output stream on the display.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] In most operating systems predating Unix, programs had to explicitly connect to the appropriate input and output devices.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] OS-specific intricacies caused this to be a tedious programming task.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] On many systems it was necessary to obtain control of environment settings, access a local file table, determine the intended data set, and handle hardware correctly in the case of a punch card reader, magnetic tape drive, disk drive, line printer, card punch, or interactive terminal.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] One of Unix's several groundbreaking advances was *abstract devices*, which removed the need for a program to know or care what kind of devices it was communicating with.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Older operating systems forced upon the programmer a record structure and frequently non-orthogonal data semantics and device control.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Unix eliminated this complexity with the concept of a data stream: an ordered sequence of data bytes which can be read until the end of file.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] A program may also write bytes as desired and need not, and cannot easily declare their count or grouping.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] In contrast, previous operating systems usually required some—often complex—job control language to establish connections, or the equivalent burden had to be orchestrated by the program.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Since Unix provided standard streams, the Unix C runtime environment was obliged to support it as well.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] As a result, most C runtime environments (and C's descendants), regardless of the operating system, provide equivalent functionality.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Standard input is a stream from which a program reads its input data.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] The program requests data transfers by use of the *read* operation.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] For example, the *dir* and *ls* programs (which display file names contained in a directory) may take command-line arguments, but perform their operations without any stream data input.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Unless redirected, standard input is inherited from the parent process.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] In the case of an interactive shell, that is usually associated with the input device of a terminal (or pseudo terminal) which is ultimately linked to a user's keyboard.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] On POSIX systems, the file descriptor for standard input is 0 (zero); the POSIX `<unistd.h>` definition is `STDIN_FILENO`; the corresponding C `<stdio.h>` abstraction is provided via the `stdin` (of type `FILE*`) global variable.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Similarly in C++, the global object `std::cin` (of type `std::istream`). provided in `<iostream>`, provides an abstraction via C++ streams.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Similar abstractions exist in the standard I/O libraries of practically every programming language.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Standard output is a stream to which a program writes its output data.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] The program requests data transfer with the *write* operation.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] For example, the *file rename* command (variously called *mv*, *move*, or *ren*) is silent on success.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Unless redirected, standard output is inherited from the parent process.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] In the case of an interactive shell, that is usually the text terminal which initiated the program.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Standard error is another output stream typically used by programs to output error messages or diagnostics.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] It is a stream independent of standard output and can be redirected separately.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] This solves the semi-predicate problem, allowing output and errors to be distinguished, and is analogous to a function returning a pair of values – see Semipredicate problem § Multivalued return.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] The usual destination is the text terminal which started the program to provide the best chance of being seen even if *standard output* is redirected (so not readily observed).
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] For example, output of a program in a pipeline is redirected to input of the next program or a text file, but user prompts and errors from each program still go directly to the text terminal so they can be reviewed by the user in real time.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] It is acceptable and normal to direct *standard output* and *standard error* to the same destination, such as the text terminal.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Messages appear in the same order as the program writes them, unless buffering is involved.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] For example, in common situations the standard error stream is unbuffered but the standard output stream is line-buffered; in this case, text written to standard error later may appear on the terminal earlier, if the standard output stream buffer is not yet full.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] The file descriptor for standard error is defined by POSIX as 2 (two); the *<unistd.h>* header file provides the symbol `STDERR_FILENO`; the corresponding C `<stdio.h>` variable is `stderr` (of type `FILE*`).
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Similarly, C++ provides two global objects associated with this stream: `std::cerr` and `std::clog` (each of type `std::ostream`), in `<iostream>`, with the former being unbuffered and the latter using the same buffering mechanism as all other C++ streams.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Standard error was added to Unix in the 1970s after several wasted phototypesetting runs ended with error messages being typeset instead of displayed on the user's terminal.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Fortran has the equivalent of Unix file descriptors: By convention, many Fortran implementations use unit numbers `UNIT=5` for stdin, `UNIT=6` for stdout and `UNIT=0` for stderr.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] In Fortran 2003, the intrinsic `ISO_FORTRAN_ENV` module was standardized to include the named constants `INPUT_UNIT`, `OUTPUT_UNIT`, and `ERROR_UNIT` to portably specify the unit numbers.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] ALGOL 60 was criticized for having no standard file access.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] ALGOL 68's input and output facilities were collectively referred to as the transput.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Koster coordinated the definition of the *transput* standard.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] The model included three standard channels: `stand in`, `stand out`, and `stand back`.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] In the C programming language, the standard input, output, and error streams are attached to the existing Unix file descriptors 0, 1 and 2 respectively.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] In a POSIX environment the *<unistd.h>* definitions STDIN_FILENO, STDOUT_FILENO or STDERR_FILENO should be used instead rather than magic numbers.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] File pointers stdin, stdout, and stderr are also provided.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Ken Thompson (designer and implementer of the original Unix operating system) modified sort in Version 5 Unix to accept "-" as representing standard input, which spread to other utilities and became a part of the operating system as a special file in Version 8.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Diagnostics were part of standard output through Version 6, after which Dennis M.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Ritchie created the concept of standard error.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] In C++, writing to standard streams was originally done using the `<iostream>` header and its streams, until the release of `<print>` which simplified input/output using print functions.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] C++ inherits C I/O facilities, but it is considered more idiomatic to use the newer C++ facilities.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] In Java, the standard streams are referred to by `System.in` (for stdin), `System.out` (for stdout), and `System.err` (for stderr).
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] It is also possible to read from any input stream using a `Scanner`.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] In C# and other .NET languages, the standard streams are referred to by `System.Console.In` (for stdin), `System.Console.Out` (for stdout) and `System.Console.Error` (for stderr).
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Basic read and write capabilities for the stdin and stdout streams are also accessible directly through the class `System.Console` (e.g.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] `System.Console.WriteLine()` can be used instead of `System.Console.Out.WriteLine()`).
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] `System.Console.In`, `System.Console.Out` and `System.Console.Error` are respectively `System.IO.TextReader` (stdin) and `System.IO.TextWriter` (stdout, stderr) objects, which only allow access to the underlying standard streams on a text basis.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Full binary access to the standard streams must be performed through the `System.IO.Stream` objects returned by `System.Console.OpenStandardInput()`, `System.Console.OpenStandardOutput()` and `System.Console.OpenStandardError()` respectively.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] When applying the `System.Diagnostics.Process` class one can use the instance properties `StandardInput`, `StandardOutput`, and `StandardError` of that class to access the standard streams of the process.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] The following example, written in Python, shows how to redirect the standard input both to the standard output and to a text file.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] In C++23, an updated printing interface was created for writing to the output stream, using `std::print` functions.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Graphical user interfaces (GUIs) do not always make use of the standard streams; they do when GUIs are wrappers of underlying scripts and/or console programs, for instance the Synaptic package manager GUI, which wraps apt commands in Debian and/or Ubuntu.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] GUIs created with scripting tools like Zenity and KDialog by KDE project make use of stdin, stdout, and stderr, and are based on simple scripts rather than a complete GUI programmed and compiled in C/C++ using Qt, GTK, or other equivalent proprietary widget framework.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] The Services menu, as implemented on NeXTSTEP and Mac OS X, is also analogous to standard streams.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] On these operating systems, graphical applications can provide functionality through a system-wide menu that operates on the current selection in the GUI, no matter in what application.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Some GUI programs, primarily on Unix, still write debug information to standard error.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Others (such as many Unix media players) may read files from standard input.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] Popular Windows programs that open a separate console window in addition to their GUI windows are the emulators pSX and DOSBox.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] GTK-server can use stdin as a communication interface with an interpreted program to realize a GUI.
[src:clap-cli-rust/standard-streams] The Common Lisp Interface Manager paradigm "presents" GUI elements sent to an extended output stream.
[src:clap-cli-rust/usage-message] In computer programming, a **usage message** or **help message** is a brief message displayed by a program that utilizes a command-line interface for execution.
[src:clap-cli-rust/usage-message] This message usually consists of the correct command line usage for the program and includes a list of the correct command-line arguments or options acceptable to said program.
[src:clap-cli-rust/usage-message] Usage messages are utilized as a quick way for a program to inform the user of proper command syntax, and should not be substituted for proper error messages or for detailed documentation such as a man page.
[src:clap-cli-rust/usage-message] A usage statement is not an error message, and thus it should generally only be printed when specifically requested by the user (via `--help`, or `-h`, or `-?`, or some similar flag or argument).
[src:clap-cli-rust/usage-message] If the user fails to pass the correct number of arguments, for example, a single line stating that an argument is missing is far more useful than several pages of output providing a general usage.
